The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan drew this time from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Centre have developed this little robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Trademark Management, BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Security Shield.
This robot will allow branded vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal space of an oval shape that looks much like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important is the compound eyes of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers developed what is called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles within a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to the microprocessor immediately to avoid the obstacle.
"When he detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forging his wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The greatest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Movement Laboratory and Chief Engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the little robot can avoid obstacles.
" Every second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to retain the information or intuitive logics of prior manoeuvres, that is why it can function continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise us, but we are not talking about giga-bytes of memory or even megabytes."
This represents the first because of the development of new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced into serial cars in about ten years after Nissan.
The robot runs with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding road obstacles.
