On Monday, paper has already received a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial organization was also looking for private buyers, but had not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not be concerned, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's clientele circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also purchased leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate on the basis of information regarding their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information on prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This type of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is to entrust its chicken to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions for drugs in Washington Post.
Insurance companies rely on insurance premiums and insured capital in the event of damage, the client's health status, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even secure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after they learned of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much less expensive procedure: from an identification number, he provides easily with pharmaceuticals, data on the purchase of the person's drugs within the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person is suffering and what his or her health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high blood fat rate, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is nothing left to do to the insurer except paperwork. However, small problems may still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or against heat suffocates, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, and they have to ask the patient for permission before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
At present, they are forced by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their past failures.
In recent years, some companies have also treated the results of laboratory analyses, linking them with data on drug use, thus providing an even more precise picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the supervisory circle of authorities concerning companies specialized in the provision of data is currently before the Congress.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is not sufficient and that is why he has developed further ahead of his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her agreement or not, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So and ultimately, the chickens depend on the kindness of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are multiplying their trade by two.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a French-India summit where cooperation on atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power to which a broader right of speech should be given in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They were not too focused on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the José Manuel Barroso Commission and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would multiply by two trades, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not appear to be too ambitious.
In this regard, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, and in this way air trade will also be able to expand in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only in the ninth place among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgent need to hold a United Nations conference on this subject was raised.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been requested, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce by at least twenty per cent its release of toxic materials by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the need for a global market to be made at the next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent the rise in food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now going to the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the press agency's information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
